{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Reform intestacy rules when a spouse dies following a conditional divorce order",
        "additional_details": "At present a spouse inherits most or all of the deceased's estate automatically if there is no will, even if a divorce is nearing completion. They are also entitled to become the administrator of the estate, and so have total control over funeral and burial arrangements. We believe this is not fair.\r\n \r\nSpouses should not automatically inherit under intestacy rules when a conditional divorce order has been granted. In these circumstances the spouse should only have the same rights as a divorcee. They should also not be entitled to become the administrator of the estate, and so have the power to decide on funeral and burial arrangements.\r\n",
        "background": "We want the Government to remove the automatic rights of a person to inherit when their spouse dies after a conditional divorce order has been granted, and the right of the spouse to become the administrator for the deceased, and so determine funeral and burial arrangements.",
